 the ongoing quest for pleasant company. Bybee argues that the very features that make civility ineffective and undesirable also point to civility's power and appeal. Can we all get along? If we live by the contradictions on which civility depends, then yes, we can, and yes, we should.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCourtesyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aFreedom of expressionzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 4aUnited States. 4acivility. 4afree speech. 4agood manners. 4ahypocrisy. 4aparadox. 4apolitics. 4apublic affairs. 4arudeness. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360182640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601826423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601826.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles